reviews.review_text: Wonderful place. Delicious food, really welcoming staff, beautiful views. We called in one afternoon for tea and cake and returned a few days later for lunch. It was all very tasty and the Fish Fridays (evening meal) looked great too. Definitely worth making a bee line for this special place.

reviews.review_text:
We had been driving for hours on Nc500, and could not find a cafe to eat which was open. We then saw the sign for the Wee Whistle Stop Cafe and headed there.
We walked in and sat at a table, there are about 7 tables, so quite small, inside a community Center.  The waitress came over to take our order, seemed confused when we said as a party we wanted to order separately, we ordered our food and drinks which they asked so many questions it was very awkward. After 15 minutes none of us had received drinks. When questioned this she went into kitchen and said. So sorry your slipped gone under something. They are coming now.
We ordered a milk shake at ¬£6.50! Yep ¬£6.50 it came in a pint bottle and a straw! That was it, nothing special just milk with vanilla flavouring. extortionate !! Cans of pop were ¬£2.50 each ! Coke came in a  small glass bottle at ¬£2.50!
Breakfast was ¬£12.50, 2 sausages, 2bacon, 2 eggs, black pudding and toast. The toast was the end of a loaf of bread, dry and cold. The remainder was ok this took almost 30 minutes. Our friends food came out another 10 minutes later.
Mug of black coffee was ¬£3.00 this was instant coffee in a mug.
The older lady who served the food had no smile. She Reached over my husband‚Äôs food to place another plate down. She told our friend to not talk on the phone and reminded him he was in a restaurant even though it was a
Small cafe in a community center.

When we left there was no bye from any of the staff when we said bye and thank you.

Sadly we would never return to this cafe. Yes it‚Äôs the only one for miles on The NC500 you would thought they would be much more welcoming !!!

reviews.review_text: Lovely caf√©, welcoming people and great food & coffee. Fantastic views out to the surrounding hills and area too. My only complaint was a lack of prices for breakfast items; our eggs & salmon on toast came out at ¬£11 each, a little on the pricey side, which we would have been happy with but would have liked to have known in advance!

reviews.review_text: A quaint little cafe overlooking loch torridon. Quite pricey, and not big servings for what you pay, although it's a captive market. The bacon was lovely, as were the coffees. Service very friendly and in reasonable time, but probably wouldn't go back as wasn't a great choice on the menu and again, very expensive. Make sure to visit the little gallery above the cafe.

translations.en: A quaint little cafe overlooking loch torridon. Quite pricey, and not big servings for what you pay, although it's a captive market. The bacon was lovely, as were the coffees. Service very friendly and in reasonable time, but probably wouldn't go back as wasn't a great choice on the menu and again, very expensive. Make sure to visit the little gallery above the cafe.

reviews.review_text: Nice to have a cafe open in this isolated spot. But sadly the food was a massive let down for the price. Both toasties were thin on toppings, the ¬£5 bucket (large mug) of fries were generic frozen fare. Worst of all my garlic mushroom toasty should be re titled greasy mushroom. No seasoning in either.

translations.en: Nice to have a cafe open in this isolated spot. But sadly the food was a massive let down for the price. Both toasties were thin on toppings, the ¬£5 bucket (large mug) of fries were generic frozen fare. Worst of all my garlic mushroom toasty should be re titled greasy mushroom. No seasoning in either.

reviews.review_text: We ate here twice this week, the smoked salmon salad and delicious dressing was the best I've had. Fresh and lemony (tasted like organic) and a large portion too. The Fritata was perfectly cooked and gluten free bread provided too! You could not wish for more, thank you to the star chef and friendly helpful waitress, we shall be back!

reviews.review_text:
We recently attempted to visit for a quick lunch. Our party consisted of four people and three dogs. Due to the rain, we approached a young waiter to inquire if the establishment was dog-friendly. He responded, "I think so," so we took a seat at a secluded table.

Shortly thereafter, we were approached by an individual, presumably the owner, who very rudely and passive-aggressively stated, "One dog at a time, I can serve you outside" (despite the rain). He added that accommodating three dogs was too much to expect of the caf√©. This comment was unnecessary and quite embarrassing in front of other patrons.

To clarify, the one-dog policy applies to the entire caf√©‚Äîif there is already a dog present, you will be turned away. We have never had issues at other 'dog-friendly' cafes in the area, and our dogs are extremely well-behaved. While we respect a one-dog policy if that is the case, we did not appreciate the manner in which it was communicated. We left immediately and will not be returning.

If you have a dog or multiple dogs, do not visit this caf√©‚Äîyou will not be welcomed. What a disappointment.
